solution.p:
Isolate x by "undoing" each operation in order: perform the opposite operations.


            3\sqrt{x-4} \amp = 15 \amp\amp \blert{\text{Divide both sides by 3.}}


            \sqrt{x-4} \amp = 5 \amp\amp \blert{\text{Square both sides.}}


            x-4 \amp = 25 \amp\amp \blert{\text{Add 4 to both sides.}}


            x \amp = 29


When we square both sides of an equation, we should check for extraneous solutions.
    3\sqrt{\alert{29}-4} = 3\sqrt{25} = 3(5)=15
Because setting x=29 does not cause us to take the square root of a negative number, the solution is 29.

Clear the fraction by multiplying both sides by (x-1).


            \dfrac{24}{x-1} \blert{(x-1)} \amp = 4 \blert{(x-1)} \amp\amp \blert{\text{Multiply by}~(x-1).}


            24 \amp = 4(x-1) \amp\amp \blert{\text{Divide both sides by 4.}}


            6 \amp = x-1 \amp\amp \blert{\text{Add 1 to both sides.}}


            7 \amp = x 


Substituting 7 into x-1, we see that 7 does not cause the denominator to be 0, so 7 is the solution.

li.p:


                 x^2+y^2 \amp = 9 \amp\amp \blert{\text{Subtract}~x^2~\text{from both sides.}}


                y^2 \amp = 9 - x^2 \amp\amp \blert{\text{Take square roots.}}


                y \amp = \pm \sqrt{9-x^2}


The two functions are ~y = \sqrt{9-x^2}~ and ~y = -\sqrt{9-x^2}~.

Substitute x=1 into each equation.
        y = \sqrt{9-(\alert{1})^2} = \sqrt{9-1} = \sqrt{8} = 2\sqrt{2}
        One point is (1,2\sqrt{2}).  Similarly, the other point is (1,-2\sqrt{2}).
